Recently heard a reading of her poem "Retreating Wind", and those lines about our souls have been on my mind.

***

*Retreating Wind*

When I made you, I loved you.
Now I pity you.

I gave you all you needed:
bed of earth, blanket of blue air‚Äî

As I get further away from you
I see you more clearly.
Your souls should have been immense by now,
not what they are,
small talking things‚Äî

https://arstechnica.com/science/2023/10/hydro-dams-are-struggling-to-handle-the-worlds-intensifying-weather/

>Like most of the world‚Äôs 58,700 large dams, those in California were built for yesterday‚Äôs more stable climate patterns. But as climate change taxes the world‚Äôs water systems‚Äîaffecting rainfall, snowmelt, and evaporation‚Äîit‚Äôs getting tough to predict how much water gets to a dam, and when. Dams are increasingly either water-starved, unable to maintain supplies of power and water for their communities, or overwhelmed and forced to release more water than desired‚Äîrisking flooding downstream.

>But at one major dam in Northern California, operators have been demonstrating how to not just weather these erratic and intense storms, but capitalize on them. Management crews at New Bullards Bar, built in 1970, entered last winter armed with new forecasting tools that gave unprecedented insight into the size and strength of the coming storms‚Äîallowing them to strategize how to handle the rain.

>First, they let the rains refill their reservoir, a typical move after a long drought. Then, as more storms formed at sea, they made the tough choice to release some of this precious hoard through their hydropower turbines, confident that more rain was coming. ‚ÄúI felt a little nervous at first,‚Äù says John James, director of resource planning at Yuba Water Agency in Northern California. Fresh showers soon validated the move. New Bullards Bar ended winter with plumped water supplies, a 150 percent boost in power generation, and a clean safety record. The strategy offers a glimpse of how better forecasting can allow hydropower to adapt to the climate change.

>Modeling studies have long suggested that better weather forecasts would be invaluable for dam managers. Now this is being confirmed in real life. New Bullards Bar is one of a half-dozen pilot sites teaming up with the US Army Corps of Engineers to test how cutting-edge forecasting can be used to optimize operations in the real world. Early tests of the methods, called forecast-informed reservoir operations, have given operators the confidence to hold 5-20 percent reserve margins beyond their reservoirs‚Äô typical capacity, says Cary Talbot, who heads the initiative for the Army Corps.

Turns out the answer was: very.

At least for our system we refuse to use terms like core and true self. We're all real and any "core" that could have existed at any point has not existed for a very long time. While we do not agree entirely with or with the terminology used but we tend to subscribe more to the Theory of Structural Dissociation which when applied to Dissociative Identity Disorder states that the formation of DID happens before the formation of a cohesive sense of self predating any potential core that could've formed. However we do believe that Autism played a massive role in our systems development as there is trauma and ways of dealing with the trauma that was only necessary because we're autistic and masking we do think played some role as some of us are far better at dealing with social situations and hiding the fact we're autistic

Footnote: The person who came up with the Theory of Structural Dissociation is also not a good person and has since publishing the theory lost his medical license for abuse of his patients and has no experience personally with the spectrum of plurality and therefore anything he said should be taken with a grain of salt. There are in fact a few professionals working in the field of Trauma and Dissociation who also have a diagnosis of DID or OSDD who have both personal and professional insight into plurality both healthy and disordered and should be listened to more as they do tend to describe real experiences more accurately.

To be quite honest none of us think there will ever be a simple all encompassing theory that could explain the myriad of ways in which plurality forms and theories like Structural Dissociation probably only accurately describe a subset of systems with DID and OSDD and some non-disordered traumagenic systems. The Brain is very complex organ and our understanding of how it works is in its infancy. - Athena
